To terminate a C program, you can use the `return` statement with a value that indicates whether the program executed successfully (usually 0) or unsuccessfully (a non-zero value). The operating system will receive this return code and take appropriate actions based on it. Here's an example of how to properly terminate a simple "Hello World" program in C:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    printf("Hello World\n");
    // Perform any necessary cleanup here
    return 0;   // Indicate successful execution
}
```

In this case, we print out our message using `printf`, then return 0 to indicate success. If your program encounters errors or unexpected conditions, you may want to return a different value instead. Just remember to always include a `return` statement at the end of your `main()` function!
